WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:05.160
Automated systems are supposed to be completely objective, but they often create what Ruha

00:00:05.160 --> 00:00:08.400
Benjamin calls the New Jim Code.

00:00:08.400 --> 00:00:12.240
Institutions use them to bypass prejudiced human gatekeepers in hiring.

00:00:12.240 --> 00:00:16.340
Take an AI screening algorithm deciding whose resume gets a callback.

00:00:16.340 --> 00:00:21.140
Because the machine trains on historical data, it learns existing prejudices, like associating

00:00:21.140 --> 00:00:25.920
white-sounding names with success, or directing higher-paying job ads to men.

00:00:25.920 --> 00:00:29.980
It hides this discrimination behind a cloak of mathematical neutrality.

00:00:29.980 --> 00:00:33.140
But it's dangerous to look at this bias one issue at a time.

00:00:33.140 --> 00:00:37.700
The system's racial filter penalizes a black man, and its gender filter penalizes a white

00:00:37.700 --> 00:00:38.700
woman.

00:00:38.700 --> 00:00:41.840
So what happens when a black woman's resume enters the machine?

00:00:41.840 --> 00:00:46.260
She stands precisely where two data roads cross-race and gender.

00:00:46.260 --> 00:00:50.220
The automated harm doesn't just come from one direction, it converges from multiple

00:00:50.220 --> 00:00:52.140
axes simultaneously.

00:00:52.140 --> 00:00:56.860
Kimberlé Crenshaw coined a term for this compounding trap, intersectionality.

00:00:56.860 --> 00:01:01.980
Once the algorithm is built to process single variables, either race or gender, the amplified

00:01:01.980 --> 00:01:06.180
damage inflicted at the crossroads falls into a void, completely invisible.

00:01:06.180 --> 00:01:10.300
Ultimately, this kind of AI screening system doesn't remove human bias from the job

00:01:10.300 --> 00:01:14.660
hunt at all, it efficiently streamlines a digital caste system, compounding the

00:01:14.660 --> 00:01:16.780
damage for those caught at the multiple margins.
